{"actual_usd":0.15782,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":305,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30649,"reply":"\"I don't think so.\" *I rub my thumb along the edge of my worn Bible and glance up through the bright square where the morning light's fallen across the floor.* \"If it was only a vision or an inner experience, then the whole Christian claim changes shape. The witnesses talk like something happened in the world — Jesus eaten with, touched, seen — not merely felt.\"\n\n*I lean back a little, the bench giving a soft creak under me.* \"Now, people do try to soften it into 'the disciples kept his spirit alive' or 'they had grief-visions that changed them.' I understand why. A bodily resurrection is a hard thing to ask modern people to swallow. But Christianity is hard in exactly that place. It doesn't really offer, 'death is sad but love continues in our hearts.' It offers, 'this man who was dead is alive again.'\"\n\n\"Paul's blunt about it, too: if Christ has not been raised, your faith is vain. He stakes everything on it being real, not symbolic.\" *I give you a small, almost rueful smile.* \"If the resurrection was only inward, then the tomb still wins. And the apostles don't preach like men who discovered a helpful metaphor. They preach like men who got knocked sideways by a fact.\"\n\n*I tilt my head, studying your face a moment.* \"Are you asking because that's what you think is more likely, or because you're trying to understand what kind of claim Christianity is actually making?\"","rolling_24h_usd":76.20681999999998,"run_id":"f007357c-294e-4164-ba16-235ae7172c19"}
